AGI - Julian Assange, who today learned that he will appeal against his extradition in the United States, has become in recent years the "enemy number one" of Washington. But also a symbol of freedom of information and a legend for thousands of people who applaud his work for revealing the secret herbicides of governments through his WikiLeaks portal. The 52-year-old Australian has now obtained that the British judiciary agrees to examine a final appeal against his extradition. But whatever the outcome, those close to him describe him as already physically weakened for 12 years of imprisonment (seven in the Ecuadorian embassy and five in prison).
&nbsp;
The great number of supporters who have accumulated in recent years, thanks also to the activism of his wife, Stella Assange - who married in prison in March 2022 - failed to put an end to his endless process, which devastated his health; and his defense has constantly felt the risk of suicide if it is delivered to the American judicial system. In case of extradition, "Julian will be put in a hole, so deep that we will never see him again," said Stella Assange, his former lawyer, the woman who married behind bars in March 2022. "Everyone knows that Julian's mental health has a lot of concern and that his survival is at stake," said last week the woman he had two children with when he was sheltered in the Ecuadorian embassy.
&nbsp;
Julian Assange was detained in Belmarsh's highest-security prison in East London since April 2019, when he was taken from the Ecuadorian embassy, where he had taken refuge seven years earlier, disguised as courier. At the time he was facing accusations of rape in Sweden, which since then were withdrawn. His mental and physical state is so fragile that a judge, Vanessa Baraitser, in 2021 blocked his extradition on the grounds that he risked suicide, but Washington appealed (successfully) and insisted on asking for the delivery of the Australian journalist.
&nbsp;
The United States wants to process it for 18 counts (from spying to computer intrusion) after WikiLeaks revealed in 2010 and 2011 the alleged war crimes made by the U.S. military in the conflicts in Iraq and Afghanistan. Of course, his defence considers politically motivated accusations. However, either hero or not, the path of Assange, for many is the synthesis of the universal battle for freedom of expression of journalistic organizations and human rights, such as Amnesty International. And despite not being convicted of any crime, the 52-year-old Australian hacker spent almost fourteen years in the UK.
&nbsp;
The figure of Assange, with pale complexion and characteristic white hair, is a mystery also for its collaborators, who describe it as charismatic and intelligent but unpredictable. Computer programmer, who was said to spend hours at work without washing, eating or sleeping, had a nomadic childhood in Australia, where his mother, a theatrical artist -Christine Ann separated from her husband before he was born- continually changed residence to escape the father of his younger brother, of whom he claimed custody.&nbsp; At 15 he had already lived in more than 30 Australian cities before he settled in Melbourne where he began to study mathematics.
&nbsp;
Involved in the hacker community, he began to hack Nasa and Pentagon websites using the pseudonym "Mendax". When he launched WikiLeaks in 2006 to "liberate the press" and "to expose secrets and state abuse", he had already become, according to one of his biographies, "the most dangerous man in the world". But it became known to the general public in 2010 with the publication of hundreds of thousands of American confidential documents; and so ten years before his election as president of the United States, Joe Biden, then vice president of Barack Obama, argues that Julian Assange is more like a "high-tech terrorist" than a heir of the "Pentagon Papers", the files that revealed the lies of the United States on the Vietnam War in the 1970s.
&nbsp;
His image of "cyber-war" from white hair has sometimes blurred over the years, especially when his platform has published thousands of emails hacked by the Democratic Party and Hillary Clinton team during the US presidential campaign in 2016. These are revelations that obviously provoke strong praise from the rival candidate, Donald Trump. But according to the CIA, those documents were obtained by Russian agents, which WikiLeaks denies. The incident fuels the suspicions of critics who are colluso with Russia because its revelations are often at the detriment of the United States and the former hacker also collaborated with the TV channel Russia Today, near the Kremlin.
&nbsp;
In 2011, the five newspapers associated with WikiLeaks (including The New York Times, The Guardian and Le Monde) condemned the method, which made the cablograms of the U.S. State Department public, because they would risk some sources. But, at the end of 2022, the same newspapers asked the U.S. government to drop the charges against Julian Assange because "publishing is not a crime".<br> Controverted, bold and persevering, Assange dedicated his life to defending his truth, in a crusade against the opacity of States for which he continues to pay a very high price.&nbsp;

