AGI - There were no survivors on the helicopter of Iranian President Ebrahim Raisi, crashed yesterday in the mountains in the northwest of the country, returning from a trip to Azerbaijan. There were nine people on the helicopter, including a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-20/chi-era-ministro-esteri-iraniano-morto-con-raisi-26455913/"> Foreign Minister Hossein Amir-Abdollahian</a>. Raisi's death was announced by the Iranian media and the Al Jazeera broadcaster >ma has not been the official proclamation by the government. However, the Red Crescent does not leave room for any hope. The images of the wreck taken from afar show intact only the tail of the helicopter, while the cockpit is crushed and completely burned. After the accident, in the night and early hours of dawn, the frenetic search by the numerous rescue teams, beyond a seventy, complicated by weather conditions.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
To identify the area of the disaster was a drone sent by Turkey, which detected heat sources, thus allowing rescuers to locate the helicopter, from which no sign of life came. All countries in the region have offered solidarity and assistance. Turkey, at the request of Tehran, had sent a helicopter equipped with night viewers, along with 32 experts in rescue at altitude. Help offers had also arrived from Emirates, Oman, India but also from Saudi Arabia, an old enemy of the Islamic Republic. Russia activated by sending a team with 47 specialists, off-road vehicles and a BO-105 helicopter.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> The recovery of the bodies
The Iranian Red Crescent declared that the bodies of Raisi and other deaths in a helicopter crash were then recovered and that the research operations ended. "We are transferring the bodies of martyrs to Tabriz," in the north-west of Iran, said to state TV Pirhossein Koolivand, head of the organization in Iran, adding that "research operations have come to an end."
<h2> Who was Raisi</h2>
Ebrahim Raisi was born in 1960 in Mashhad, the holy Shiite city in the north-east of the country and graduated in Islamic law at the Motahari University of Tehran. In his 'curriculum' participation in the Khomeinist revolution, appointing it to provincial prosecutor in 1981, head of the National Inspection Office in 1994 and to Attorney General from 2014 to 2016. He was first vice president of the Supreme Court, from 2004 to 2014, then president from 2019 to 2021, when he was appointed president of Iran. The vice president of Iran, Mohammad Mokhber, is the first in the power line after President Ebrahim Raisi. According to the Iranian constitution, in the event of the death or incapacity of the president, the first vice-president falls and assumes the functions of president until the election takes place within a maximum period of 50 days.
&nbsp;
Unlike other countries, the first Iranian vice-presidentship is a nominated, unelected position. The Vice-President assumed some of the powers of the Prime Minister after the office was abolished in 1989. There are several appointed vice-presidents who serve at the same time in Iran and work mainly as members of the cabinet. The charge covered by Mokhber is considered first among peers. Raisi appointed Mokhber his first vice president in August 2021> shortly after he entered office. She is the seventh person to cover that role after the revision of the country's constitution. Prior to his appointment as vice president, Mokhber was for 14 years at the head of the Iranian Setad, a powerful economic conglomerate focused mainly on charitable causes. &nbsp;&nbsp;
