AGI - The situation remains very tense in New Caledonia>, where the closure of the airport was extended while the territory is still in prey to blocks despite the huge resources committed by the State to restore order. The French president, Emmanuel Macron>, called for today at 18.30 a Defence Council to cope with the incandescent situation of the territory of Oltremare, where a week is underway a <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-16/new-caledonia-caos-state-emergency-26399709/" During the tumults, marked by barricades, fires and clashes, six people have so far lost their lives.
&nbsp;
Among the difficulties of keeping the situation under control, the international airport of Noumea > which will remain closed to commercial flights until 12 of next Thursday, announced today the manager of the platform. And this despite the repeated requests from Australia and New Zealand to be able to evacuate their countrymen.
&nbsp;
Macron chaired last Wednesday the first Defence Council of New Caledonia, which had ended with the establishment of the state of emergency. A second, Thursday, had prepared the massive sending of police and gendarmerie reinforcements in the territory, where police forces now exceed 2,700. Yesterday morning an operation of 600 gendarmes was launched, including some leather heads, to "restore the order", especially on the strategic axis of about fifty kilometers that connects Nouméa to the international airport of La Tontouta, blocked in several points by the independentists. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"The Republican Order will be restored at any cost," said the High Commissioner of the French Government Louis Le Franc>. If the separatists "want to use weapons, they will risk the worst", warned the official in a press conference broadcast by public television of the territory, "I want to tell the riots: Stop, calm down, deliver your weapons."

