AGI - In the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-20/raisi-morto-incident- helicopter-26453916/"> accident costing life to Ebrahim Raisi</a> the Iranian Foreign Minister Hossein Amirabdollahian also died. In recent months he had conducted extensive diplomatic activity against Israel, threatening and criticizing on every occasion during an intense tour of the region that had taken him to Iraq, Lebanon, Syria and Qatar. He said, for example, that "it is time to punish Israel and establish an international commission to investigate its crimes" and that "the Israeli enemy is in the swamp of Gaza thanks to the firmness and resistance of the Palestinian people".
&nbsp;
He repeatedly accused "the Israeli regime of threatening regional security," and after the Israeli Air Force attack on Iran warned that Tehran would make "immediate passes against Israel" if he had "tened to attack again". Amirabdollahiyan was appointed Foreign Minister by Raisi in 2021. The television broadcaster of Qatar "Al-Jazeera" noted that it is in good relations with the Iranian supreme leader Ali Khamenei and with various elements of the "Asse della Resistenza" - of which Hamas, Hezbollah and the Houthi - and in particular with the Shiite organization Hassan Nasrallah. He was also considered in good relations with the Guardian of the Revolution and with Qasem Soleimani, the commander of the Al-Quds Brigades eliminated in an American attack in 2020. He had an academic education and had published several books and articles of politics and international relations.
<div </div
At the beginning of his career in Iranian politics, he held several diplomatic positions in the Middle East and established close ties with many anti-Israeli leaders. One of his first assignments was the deputy ambassador of Iran in Baghdad between 1997 and 2001. Afterwards he had dealt with the Gulf issues at the Iranian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and had also been active in matters relating to the Iran nuclear agreement. Moreover, he had worked to promote relations with China and Russia, and during his term relations between Iran and Saudi Arabia were renewed.
&nbsp;
In recent days Amirabdollahiyan had spoken with UN Secretary General Antonio Guterres of Israeli activity in Rafah. "If Washington will allow Netanyahu to commit new crimes to Rafah, the consequences will be serious," said the minister, "Washington must choose between showing the desire to end the war in Gaza and bringing the region to a new level of tension." In the last month he had numerous talks with his homologues in Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Qatar, accusing Israel to increase tensions in the region and in the first days of war he had met both the head of the political office of Hamas, Ismail Haniyeh and the official spokesman of the Houthi, Muhammad Abd Sala.
&nbsp;
His most probable successor is the Deputy Foreign Minister, Ali Bagheri Kani, critical ferocious of the Iranian nuclear agreement of 2015 or the Joint Global Action Plan (JCPOA). Born in October 1967 in the northwestern Kan district of Tehran, he obtained a Ph.D. in Economics at Imam Sadegh University, incubator for careers of some of the most trusted officials of the Iranian regime and managed by the Bagheri Kani family for 40 years. Many nuclear scientists and intelligence agents trained in this elite academy, including the daughter of Khamenei, Hoda, and her husband Mesbah ol-Hoda.&nbsp;
