AGI - The Israeli flag waved on the Gaza side of the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-19/onu-800mila-persone-costrette-a-fuggire-da-rafah-26443631/"> raft of Rafah/a> for two weeks even if Egypt refused to reopen Cairo has thus in fact held (almost perennially) closed one of the only points through which the aids, of which there is extreme need, can reach the Strip and its population.&nbsp; The impasse, writes Afp, has aggravated that terrible humanitarian catastrophe that are already living the 2.4 million inhabitants of the Palestinian territory. It is no coincidence that, more than 7 months from the beginning of the war between Hamas and Israel, the alarms of "a looming famine" have been repeated.
&nbsp;
The Rafah Pass, on the southern border of Gaza, was the symbol of Hamas' control over the Palestinian territory since 2007 but&nbsp; at the beginning of May the Israeli army completed a rapid control of the passage, which according to the army was "used for terrorist purposes". Since then it has been closed, strongly limiting the volume of aid that has arrived in Gaza. Before the Israeli tanks entered into action, Hamas - designated as a "terrorist" group from Israel, the United States and the European Union - was usually to collect taxes on goods passing through the passageway. Israel and others also suspect that the Rafah Pass was used in the past to bring weapons into the Gaza Strip.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The hypothesis on future management of the vessel
Since the beginning of the war, triggered by the Hamas attack on Israel on October 7, most deliveries of aid to Gaza have passed through Rafah. In the weeks prior to the Israeli army's settlement, according to UN data, about 100 aid trucks had entered every day through the Egyptian passage, as well as most crucial fuel supplies. Already a day later, the Israeli seizure, the media declared that the government was exploring its options to understand what to do with the passage itself. The left-wing newspaper Haaretz stated that Israel had begun negotiations with Egypt and the United States to give way to a private US company. Some analysts said they were skeptical about this possibility by citing the likely opposition of Palestinian armed groups that would make operations risky or impossible. Hamas militants have already claimed several missile attacks against Israeli troops deployed at the key points of the terminal. Egypt refused to coordinate with Israel on the Rafah Pass and on Wednesday the media said that Cairo rejected an Israeli proposal to reopen it.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The Israeli and Palestinian media reported another Israeli proposal, this time addressed to the Palestinian Authority (AP), based in the West Bank occupied and controlled by the rival of Hamas, Fatah, the party of President Mahmud Abbas.&nbsp; According to reports, the proposal would formally give the AP control of the passage, but operations would be managed by a group considered neutral, such as the Red Crescent Society. The AP refused, insisting that it will take control of the vessel only if it will be given full authority in the management of the vessel.
<h2>E l'Onu?</h2>
Since Israel retired from Gaza in 2005 and until the power of Hamas in 2007, the Rafah Pass was under the control of the Palestinian Authority. A broad agreement, led by Washington, had entrusted control to the agents of the AP, however guaranteeing Israel the right of supervision. The EUBAM gendarmes, a European mission, were also present at the crossing on the basis of the 2005 agreement. A European official in Jerusalem told the Afp on condition of anonymity, that the EUBAM was contacted recently. But the source said that Europeans would refuse to participate in the management of the vessel if the Palestinian Authority had not been involved. A EU diplomat based in Tel Aviv, who asked for an anonymity as unauthorized to speak publicly of the matter, told the French agency that the embassy was asked about the Rafah Pass. "I don't think it's likely to be our direct involvement," said the diplomat, stressing the complexity of creating a European mission in the terminal and the "humanitarian emergency" that his government considers responsibility for Israel. In this context, the United Nations also remains a potential partner.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The United Nations agency for Palestinian refugees, the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-14/medium-orient-idf-public-video-Palestinian-armed-in-base-unrwa-26387406/">UNRWA</a>, has never managed Rafah's pass but has played a central role in managing the Palestinian refugees. But Israel's ties with UNRWA and other United Nations bodies, which have long been thesis, have been further depressed during the war and it is unlikely that the government will entrust the keys to the air transport agency. Since the beginning of the war, UNRWA has been the subject of a burst of criticism by Israelis, with high Israeli leaders and ministers accused of collusion with Hamas, while offering few evidence. The UN agency, for its part, strongly denied Israel's compliant arguments.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
